<DOC><DOCNO> AP880725-0014 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 0052EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-SpeedTrapFlap     07-25 0254</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Speed Trap Flap,0260</SECOND><HEAD>German Politicians Reported Angered By New Italian Speed Limits</HEAD><DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Some West German politicians arecalling lowered speed limits on Italian highways downrightinhospitable, saying they appear aimed at catching unsuspectingGerman vacationers unawares.   ``The purpose of this law is apparently to take money fromvacationers,'' the mass-circulation newspaper Bild quoted federallawmaker Ernt Hinken as saying.   ``Many Germans will be caught without knowing the law has beenchanged,'' Hinken, a federal lawmaker for the governing ChristianDemocrats, reportedly told the paper.   Under new rules that took effect on Sunday, the maximum speedpermitted on Italy's superhighways has been lowered to 110kilometers per hour (68 mph) from 140 kilometers per hour (87 mph).The maximum speed on Italy's regular highways fell to 90 from 110kilometers per hour.   Italian authorities said the speed limits were lowered becauseof an increase in highway deaths.   Thousands of West Germans are now taking to the road _ many ofthem en route to Italy and other southern points _ to start theirsummer vacations.   There are no maximum speed limits on some sections of WestGermany's autobahns.   Erwin Huber, a high-ranking politician with the Christian SocialUnion, the CDU's Bavarian sister party, also criticized the loweredItalian speed limits.   ``Italy is a much-beloved vacationland with a reputation forhospitality. But I do not think these measures are hospitable,''Bild quoted him as saying.   Bild's report, appearing it today's editions, was telexed toother news organizations in advance.</TEXT></DOC>